#2. Carry out a t-test to determine if profit level is statistically different between weekday and weekend.

aggregate(Profit ~IsWeekend, retail, mean)
##   IsWeekend   Profit
## 1   Weekday 28.35871
## 2   Weekend 29.24432
t.test(Profit ~ IsWeekend, retail)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Profit by IsWeekend
## t = -0.17207, df = 6123, p-value = 0.8634
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -10.974894   9.203677
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Weekday mean in group Weekend 
##              28.35871              29.24432
# The mean profit on a weekday is $28.35871. The mean profit on a weekend is $29.24432. 
# Using the t-test, the p-value of the difference between profit on weekday and profit on weekend is 0.8634.
# As the 95% confidence interval comprises p-values between -10.974894 and 9.203677, the p-value of 0.8634 is within the 95% confidence interval.
# Hence, we can be 95% confident that there is no difference in the average profit between weekday and average profit on weekend.

#3. Draw a boxplot to examine the profit by (a) segment (b) ship (c) category

# Profit by segment
boxplot(Profit ~ Segment, retail, xlab = "Segment", ylab = "Profit", main = "Profit by Segment")

# Profit by ship mode
boxplot(retail$Profit ~ retail$Ship.Mode, xlab = "Ship Mode", ylab = "Profit", main = "Profit by Ship Mode")

# Profit by category
boxplot(retail$Profit ~ retail$Category, xlab = "Category", ylab = "Profit", main = "Profit by Category")

#4. Draw a density plot for profit

plot(density(retail$Profit, from = -200, to = 200))

#5. Carry out a one-way ANOVA to test if profit is statistically different between the categories of Consumer, Corporate and Home Office found in the segment variable.

# Check that Segment data type is factor
str(retail$Segment)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "Consumer","Corporate",..: 1 1 2 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 ...
# Check if each segment has same number of items
nrow(retail[retail$Segment == "Consumer", ])
## [1] 5191
nrow(retail[retail$Segment == "Corporate", ])
## [1] 3020
nrow(retail[retail$Segment == "Home Office", ])
## [1] 1783
# the segments do not have the same number of items

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
leveneTest(retail$Profit, retail$Segment)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##         Df F value Pr(>F)
## group    2  0.2686 0.7645
##       9991
# Since the p-value under the Levene's test is 0.7645 which is more than 0.05, this suggests that variances are not unequal and the ANOVA test is suitable

#ANOVA test
anova_test <- aov(Profit ~ Segment, retail)
summary(anova_test)
##               Df    Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## Segment        2     98570   49285   0.898  0.407
## Residuals   9991 548295266   54879
# Since the resulting p-value of 0.407 is greater than 0.05, we reject the alternative hypothesis that there are significant differences between the profits for each segment.
